==Old English==
===Etymology===
From Germanic ''*drio-, *driusa-''.  Cognate with Old Saxon [[dror|drōr]], Old High German [[tror|trōr]], Old Norse [[dreyri]].  The historical sense is of something which ‘falls’: the Germanic base is also the source of Old English [[dreosan|drēosan]] ‘fall’.

===Pronunciation===
{{IPA|/dɹe:oɹ/}}

===Noun===
'''drēor''' ''m''
# [[gore]], [[blood]]
#:''Ic his blod ageat, dreor on eorþan'': I shed his blood, his gore on the earth.

